# Pull Request Review: TAURI009 -- Auto-launch on login

## Summary

The implementation configures auto-launch at login using `@tauri-apps/plugin-autostart`. It spans the Rust backend (plugin init, permissions), the platform abstraction layer (Tauri/web implementations), and the settings UI (checkbox with optimistic state). The approach is well-structured and follows the existing codebase patterns precisely.

---

## [CRITICAL] None found

The implementation has no critical issues. The overall approach is sound.

---

## [WARNING] W1: `MacosLauncher` used unconditionally under `#[cfg(desktop)]`

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src-tauri/src/lib.rs`, line 15 and line 781

```rust
#[cfg(desktop)]
use tauri_plugin_autostart::MacosLauncher;
```

```rust
.plugin(tauri_plugin_autostart::init(MacosLauncher::LaunchAgent, None))
```

The import is gated behind `#[cfg(desktop)]`, but the `.plugin(...)` call on line 781 is **not** gated behind any `cfg` attribute -- it is in the main `run()` function body that executes unconditionally. This works today because the Cargo dependency is gated behind `cfg(any(target_os = "macos", windows, target_os = "linux"))`, but the `MacosLauncher::LaunchAgent` variant is macOS-specific. On Windows/Linux builds, `tauri-plugin-autostart` may still compile (the plugin handles it internally), but passing `MacosLauncher::LaunchAgent` to non-macOS targets is semantically misleading. If the plugin's internal handling ever changes, this becomes a build failure on Windows/Linux.

Compare with how `global-shortcut` is initialized: it is registered inside the `#[cfg(desktop)]` setup block. Consider moving the autostart plugin init into the same block, or at minimum adding a comment acknowledging the plugin handles cross-platform dispatch internally.

---

## [WARNING] W2: No user-facing error feedback on autostart toggle failure

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/settings/settings_view.tsx`, lines 628-636

```typescript
const handleAutoLaunchChange = useCallback((enabled: boolean) => {
    if (!isTauri) return;
    setAutoLaunch(enabled);
    const autostart = getPlatform().autostart;
    (enabled ? autostart.enable() : autostart.disable()).catch(err => {
      console.error(err);
      setAutoLaunch(!enabled);
    });
  }, []);
```

The optimistic update + rollback pattern is correct. However, on failure the user sees the checkbox flicker back with **no explanation**. Every other action in this settings view uses `showHUD` for user feedback. A failed autostart toggle should call `showHUD` with an error message so the user understands why the setting reverted. Silent rollbacks create confusion.

---

## [WARNING] W3: `handleAutoLaunchChange` has stale closure over `showHUD`

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/settings/settings_view.tsx`, line 636

```typescript
const handleAutoLaunchChange = useCallback((enabled: boolean) => {
    // ...
  }, []);
```

The dependency array is empty `[]`, but if you add `showHUD` for error feedback (per W2), you would need it in the dependency array. Additionally, this callback is used inside `handleResetAll` (line 774) which itself lists `handleAutoLaunchChange` as a dependency. This chain is correct as-is, but note that if you ever need to reference `showHUD` or other state inside `handleAutoLaunchChange`, the empty dependency array will cause stale closures. Currently it only uses `isTauri` (module-level constant) and `getPlatform()` (module-level function), so it happens to be safe today.

---

## [NIT] N1: Conditional rendering leaves orphan `FormSeparator` when not in Tauri

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/settings/settings_view.tsx`, lines 348-356

```tsx
<FormSeparator />
{isTauri && (
  <FormCheckbox
    label="Launch at Login"
    checked={autoLaunch}
    onChange={onAutoLaunchChange}
    description="Automatically start Raycast when you log in"
  />
)}
<FormCheckbox
  label="Show Recent Applications"
  ...
```

When `isTauri` is `false`, the `<FormSeparator />` on line 348 renders directly followed by "Show Recent Applications" with no "Launch at Login" between them. The separator is still semantically appropriate (it separates dropdowns from checkboxes), so this is fine visually. Just noting it for awareness -- the separator is not specifically tied to the autostart option.

---

## [NIT] N2: Autostart state is not persisted to the settings database

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/settings/settings_view.tsx`

The autostart state is read from the OS via `isEnabled()` on mount and toggled via `enable()`/`disable()`. It is intentionally **not** stored in the settings database -- the plugin itself is the source of truth. This is the correct approach: the OS launch agent / registry entry is the canonical state. Storing a redundant copy in the DB would create sync issues.

This is called out as a nit only to confirm this was a deliberate design decision, not an oversight.

---

## [NIT] N3: `autostart` dynamic import repeated three times

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/platform/tauri.ts`, lines 134-147

```typescript
const autostart: PlatformAutostart = {
  async enable() {
    const { enable } = await import('@tauri-apps/plugin-autostart');
    await enable();
  },
  async disable() {
    const { disable } = await import('@tauri-apps/plugin-autostart');
    await disable();
  },
  async isEnabled() {
    const { isEnabled } = await import('@tauri-apps/plugin-autostart');
    return isEnabled();
  },
};
```

This follows the exact same pattern as every other platform method in this file (clipboard, shell, files, apps all use per-call dynamic imports). It is consistent, which is the right call. The repeated `import()` calls resolve from the module cache after the first load, so there is no performance concern. Noted only for completeness.

---

## [NIT] N4: Cargo dependency version pinning

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src-tauri/Cargo.toml`, line 37

```toml
tauri-plugin-autostart = "2"
```

This matches the pattern used by `tauri-plugin-clipboard-manager = "2"` and `tauri-plugin-sql`. The JS side pins to `^2.5.1`. The Rust side allows any `2.x`. This is consistent with the rest of the project, so no change needed, but be aware that Cargo will resolve to latest `2.x` which could drift from the JS package version.

---

## Verdict

**Approve with minor suggestions.** The implementation is clean, follows all existing codebase patterns, and the platform abstraction is consistent. The two warnings worth addressing before merge:

1. **W1** -- Consider wrapping the autostart plugin init in the `#[cfg(desktop)]` block for explicitness, or at minimum confirming the plugin handles non-macOS targets gracefully with `MacosLauncher::LaunchAgent`.
2. **W2** -- Add `showHUD` feedback when the autostart toggle fails, matching the UX pattern used everywhere else in this view.
